'''''The Maze of Galious'''''{{efn|Known as {{nihongo|'''''Majou Densetsu II: Gariusu no Meikyuu'''''|魔城伝説II ガリウスの迷宮|''Majō Densetsu Tsū: Gariusu no Meikyū''|lit. "Demon Castle Legend II: The Maze of Galious" or "Legend of the Devil Castle II: The Maze of Galious"|lead=yes}} in Japan.}} is a 1987 [[platform-adventure]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Konami]] for the [[MSX]] home computer. A reworked conversion was released for the [[Family Computer]]. Both versions were re-released digitally for [[Microsoft Windows]]. The second entry in the ''[[Knightmare (1986 video game)|Knightmare]]'' trilogy, it follows the respective hero and former [[damsel in distress]] of the previous game, Popolon and Aphrodite, as they embark on a journey through Castle Greek to free their unborn child Pampas from the evil priest Galious. The player explores each map in search for [[Item (gaming)|item]]s and [[power-up]]s to progress, while also fighting enemies and [[Boss (video gaming)|bosses]].

''The Maze of Galious'' was created by the MSX division at Konami under management of Shigeru Fukutake. The process of making original titles for the platform revolved around the person who came up with the characters. A team of seven members were responsible for its development, lasting somewhere between four and six months, with Ryouhei Shogaki being the project's lead designer. The game garnered generally favorable reception from critics and retrospective commentarists. It served as influence for ''[[La-Mulana]]'' (2006), while the game's exploration bits were utilized for ''[[Castlevania II: Simon's Quest]]''. It was followed by ''[[Shalom: Knightmare III]]'' (1987). In the years since, fans have experimented with remaking and porting the title unofficially to other platforms.

== Gameplay ==
[[File:MSX The Maze of Galious (Majō Densetsu II - Gariusu no Meikyū).png|frame|left|Gameplay screenshot of the [[MSX]] version.]]
''The Maze of Galious'' is a platform-adventure game starring the warrior Popolon and his lover, the princess Aphrodite, as they embark on a journey through Castle Greek to free their unborn child Pampas from the evil priest Galious.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="TMOGumJP">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/KnightmareIITheMazeOfGalious1987KonamiJPRC749|title=魔城伝説II ガリウスの迷宮|date=April 1987|publisher=[[Konami]]|edition=Japanese|type=ユーザーマニュアル}}</ref><ref name="TMOGumEU">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/KnightmareIITheMazeOfGalious1987KonamiEURC749|title=The Maze of Galious|date=1987|publisher=[[Konami]]|edition=European|type=User's Manual}}</ref> Being able to control two characters means the player can switch between Popolon and Aphrodite, both of which have slightly different abilities: Popolon can push stones, open heavy doors and has a variable jumping height, while Aphrodite survives longer under water, can shoot more projectiles and has a fixed jumping height.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="TMOGumJP"/><ref name="TMOGumEU"/> The game's structure is similar to ''[[The Legend of Zelda (video game)|The Legend of Zelda]]''; Castle Greek acts as the main overworld, where entrances to the ten "worlds" are hidden throughout.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="TMOGumJP"/><ref name="TMOGumEU"/><ref name="InputMSX21">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/InputMSXNumero23Ano21988/Input%20MSX/Input%20MSX%2021/page/n29/mode/2up|title=Todo Sobre... — The Maze of Galious|magazine=Input MSX|issue=21|publisher=Planeta-De Agostini|date=1988|pages=30–33|language=es}}</ref>

The player explores each world map, collecting [[Item (gaming)|item]]s, defeating enemies and [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]]es, and obtaining [[power-up]]s to progress further.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="TMOGumJP"/><ref name="TMOGumEU"/><ref name="InputMSX26">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/InputMSXNumero23Ano21988/Input%20MSX/Input%20MSX%2026/page/n36/mode/1up|title=Software: The Maze of Galious|magazine=Input MSX|issue=26|publisher=Planeta-De Agostini|date=July 1988|pages=37–41|language=es}}</ref> Similar to [[metroidvania]] games, new areas can be accessed by acquiring new items.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Knightmare II: The Maze of Galious |url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/knightmare-ii-the-maze-of-galious/ |access-date=2023-01-02 |website=Hardcore Gaming 101 |language=en-US}}</ref> Each map also hosts three hidden items to aid Popolon and Aphrodite against a "Great Demon".<ref name="TMOGhg101"/> In order to face a "Great Demon", the player must inspect a gravestone that reveals an incantation to invoke them at a boss room by typing their names.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="TMOGumJP"/><ref name="TMOGumEU"/><ref name="InputMSX21"/> Some items are optional but others are mandatory such as the "Cross", which is needed to face against the final boss.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="InputMSX25">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/InputMSXNumero23Ano21988/Input%20MSX/Input%20MSX%2025/page/n50/mode/1up|title=Trucos: The Maze of Galious — Como Conseguir La Cruz|magazine=Input MSX|issue=25|publisher=Planeta-De Agostini|date=June 1988|page=51|language=es}}</ref> Enemies can drop random items after their defeat, ranging from that can be spent in shops to upgrade the character's overall inventory, arrow stocks for projectile-based weapons, and keys to open locked doors.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="TMOGumJP"/><ref name="TMOGumEU"/>

There are several types of enemies, each with strengths and weaknesses; some monsters are immune to frontal attacks, while others are more vulnerable to fire and so on. The player can also kill enemies to fill an "experience" gauge, which replenishes a character's health when full.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="TMOGumJP"/><ref name="TMOGumEU"/> Another way to heal a character is entering a special room within the main overworld map, which contains a magic dust that can be turned into a fairy by standing at a certain spot.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/> Should either character die, the other can visit a shrine and pay for resurrection.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="TMOGumJP"/><ref name="TMOGumEU"/><ref name="InputMSX21"/> If both characters perish, the [[Game over|game is over]], but the player can resume progress via passwords obtained from "Demeter's Shrine".<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="TMOGumJP"/><ref name="TMOGumEU"/> Extra content is unlocked if the ''[[Konami Game Master|Game Master]]'', ''[[Knightmare (1986 video game)|Knightmare]]'' or ''[[Q*bert]]'' are inserted in the second cartridge slot available on most MSX machines.

== Development ==
''The Maze of Galious'' was developed by the [[MSX]] division at [[Konami]] under management of Shigeru Fukutake, who revealed about the creation process in a 1988 interview with Japanese publication ''Micom BASIC Magazine''.<ref name="MBM75">{{cite magazine|last=Yamashita|first=Akira|url=https://archive.org/details/micomBASIC_1988-09/page/n251/mode/2up|title=山下章のパソコン・ゲーム: ホンキでPlayホンネでReview — TARGET 5 コナミMSXゲーム|magazine={{ill|Micom BASIC Magazine|lt=Micom BASIC Magazine|ja|マイコンBASICマガジン}}|issue=75|publisher={{ill|The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|lt=The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|ja|電波新聞社}}|date=September 1988|pages=278–282|lang=ja}} ([https://thearkhound.tumblr.com/post/187958078198/exploring-the-secret-behind-konamis-msx-games Translation] by Arc Hound. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210925132527/https://thearkhound.tumblr.com/post/187958078198/exploring-the-secret-behind-konamis-msx-games|date=2021-09-25}}).</ref> Fukutate explained that the staffer who came up with the characters was in charge of design and facilitating development of the project, as the process of making original titles for the MSX revolved around the person who came up with the characters being assigned to do both planning and the story.<ref name="MBM75"/> Fukutate further explained that the planner would then lead a team of four or five members to proceed with development, which would last somewhere between four and six months.<ref name="MBM75"/>

Seven staffers were responsible for the project: director and designer Ryouhei "Ryokun" Shogaki, programmers Masahiko "Mai" Ozawa and Yutaka "Hal" Haruki, artist Chiaki Tanigaki, composer Kazuhiko Uehara, and two members under the pseudonyms "Hipo" and "Tomoyo".<ref name="TMOGstaff">{{cite video game|title=The Maze of Galious|developer=[[Konami]]|publisher=[[Konami]]|date=April 18, 1987|platform=[[MSX]]|level=Staff}}</ref><ref name="MBM60">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/micomBASIC_1987-06/page/n295/mode/1up|title=Software House Hot Information - Konami News Station: 大好評発売中! — ガリウスの迷き 〜魔城伝説打〜|magazine={{ill|Micom BASIC Magazine|lt=Micom BASIC Magazine|ja|マイコンBASICマガジン}}|issue=60|publisher={{ill|The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|lt=The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|ja|電波新聞社}}|date=June 1987|page=296|lang=ja}} ([https://thearkhound.tumblr.com/post/183523299898/1987-maze-of-galious-qa-from-micom-basic Translation] by Arc Hound. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210714192606/https://thearkhound.tumblr.com/post/183523299898/1987-maze-of-galious-qa-from-micom-basic|date=2021-07-14}}).</ref> Other people also collaborated in its development.<ref name="TMOGstaff"/> ''Maze of Galious'' was the first game Uehara worked on after joining Konami in 1986 as sound designer; He would be responsible for creating the SCC sound chip, as well as working on ''[[Space Manbow]]'' and ''[[Metal Gear 2: Solid Snake]]''.<ref name="MSXMagJPepe3">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/MSXMAGAZINE3_201808/page/n155/mode/2up|title=We Love コナミ: SCC 上原和彦氏 インタビュー|magazine={{ill|MSX Magazine|lt=MSX Magazine|ja|MSXマガジン}}|issue=3|type=Eternal Preservation Edition [永久保存版]|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=May 12, 2005|pages=154–157|language=ja}} ([https://thearkhound.tumblr.com/post/185434872193/kazuhiko-uehara-interview-with-msx-magazine-2005 Translation] by Arc Hound. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210219071033/https://thearkhound.tumblr.com/post/185434872193/kazuhiko-uehara-interview-with-msx-magazine-2005|date=2021-02-19}}).</ref> The team revealed in a 1987 article that they never decided upon the gender of Pampas (although it was later in the MSX sequel, Shalom, that Pampas would become a king, therefore being male), while an eleventh map was scrapped due to memory constrains.<ref name="MBM60"/>

== Release ==
Prior to launch, a game titled ''Majou Densetsu II: Poporon Gekitou Hen''{{efn|{{nihongo|魔城伝説II 〜ポポロン激闘編〜|Majō Densetsu II ~Poporon Gekitō Hen~}}}} was scheduled to be published in 1987 by Konami for the [[PC-8800 series|PC-8801]] and [[X1 (computer)|X1]] home computers.<ref name="IO123">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/Io19871/page/n98/mode/1up|title=魔城伝説II 〜ポポロン激闘編〜|magazine={{ill|I/O (magazine)|lt=I/O|ja|I/O (雑誌)}}|issue=123|publisher={{ill|Kohgaku-Sha|lt=Kohgaku-Sha|ja|工学社}}|date=January 1987|page=97|language=ja}}</ref><ref name="MBM56">{{cite magazine|author=YK-2|url=https://archive.org/details/micomBASIC_1987-02/page/n267/mode/2up|title=立ちあがれ！勇者ポポロン — 魔城伝説II|magazine={{ill|Micom BASIC Magazine|lt=Micom BASIC Magazine|ja|マイコンBASICマガジン}}|issue=56|publisher={{ill|The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|lt=The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation|ja|電波新聞社}}|date=February 1987|pages=244–245|language=ja}}</ref><ref name="LOGiNv6i3">{{cite magazine|title=魔城伝説II 〜ポポロン激闘編〜|magazine={{ill|LOGiN Magazine|lt=LOGiN|ja|ログイン (雑誌)}}|volume=6|issue=3|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=March 1987|pages=196–197|language=ja}}</ref> The game was intended to be a vertical-scrolling shooter similar to ''[[Knightmare (1986 video game)|Knightmare]]'' but with [[Role-playing video game|role-playing]] elements added.<ref name="MBM56"/><ref name="LOGiNv6i3"/> It was never released for unknown reasons despite being advertised and previewed in Japanese magazines.<ref name="IO123"/><ref name="MBM56"/><ref name="LOGiNv6i3"/> ''The Maze of Galious'' was first published for the MSX in Japan on April 18, 1987, and later in Europe of that year by Konami.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/InputMSXNumero23Ano21988/Input%20MSX/Input%20MSX%2017/page/n7/mode/1up|title=Actualidad: The Maze of Galious|magazine=Input MSX|issue=17|publisher=Planeta-De Agostini|date=1987|page=8|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx2.html|title=MSX's Soft (1987～1990)|publisher=[[Konami]]|date=1996|access-date=2022-09-05|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19961108212544/http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/msx2.html|archive-date=1996-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref> A few months after the original release, a completely reworked conversion titled ''Majou Densetsu II: Daima Shikyou Gariusu''{{efn|{{nihongo|魔城伝説II 大魔司教ガリウス|Majō Densetsu II: Daima Shikyō Gariusu}}}} was released for the [[Family Computer]] exclusively in Japan by Konami on August 11, featuring changes such as improved visuals and redesigned maps.<ref name="TMOGhg101"/><ref name="MeriStatTMOG"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/fc.html|title=Famicon's Soft (1985～1987)|publisher=[[Konami]]|date=1996|access-date=2022-09-09|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19961108212502/http://www.konami.co.jp/cs/fc.html|archive-date=1996-11-08|url-status=live}}</ref>

Although it was not officially released outside Japan, an English [[Fan translation of video games|fan translation]] for the Famicom version was released online.<ref name="MeriStatTMOG"/> Both versions were first re-released in digital form for [[Microsoft Windows]] on the i-Revo store front.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.i-revo.jp/corporate/news_release/press_20060908.pdf|title=「i revo ゲーム」で 100 種類以上のゲームが遊び放題の定額課金を開始|work=i-revo|publisher=Internet Revolution|date=September 8, 2006|access-date=2022-09-06|language=ja|archive-date=2022-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220221204008/https://www.i-revo.jp/corporate/news_release/press_20060908.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://game.i-revo.jp/dl/search/displayDetail.do?productId=10012|title=ガリウスの迷宮|work=i-revo|publisher=Internet Revolution|access-date=2022-09-06|language=ja}}</ref> In 2006, the full soundtrack of the Famicom version was included as part of a compilation album titled ''Legend Of Game Music Consumer Box'', distributed in Japan by [[Scitron]].<ref name="VGMdb">{{cite web|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/6804|title=LEGEND OF GAME MUSIC CONSUMER BOX &#124; SCDC-00497~506|publisher=VGMdb|access-date=2022-09-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211128131137/https://vgmdb.net/album/6804|archive-date=2021-11-28|url-status=live}}</ref> The MSX version was also re-released in digital form for Windows through [[D4 Enterprise]]'s Project EGG service on March 24, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/008/G000896/20150324032/|title=「魔城伝説II ガリウスの迷宮（MSX版）」がプロジェクトEGGで本日配信に|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=March 24, 2015|access-date=2022-09-06|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326105333/https://www.4gamer.net/games/008/G000896/20150324032/|archive-date=2015-03-26|url-status=live}}</ref>

